1 Introduction |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-1 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
One of the major topics in the post-sequence era is the analysis of transcription regulation network. It is |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
indispensable to define precise promoter regions and transcription start sites for this analysis. To support it, |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
we have constructed the DataBase of Transcription Start Sites (DBTSS) [1,2] (http://dbtss.hgc jp). DBTSS |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
contains the information of accurate transcription start sites (TSSs) based on experimentally determined |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
5’-end clones. It currently contains 1,359,000 clones corresponding to 15,262 genes in human, as well as |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
364,487 clones corresponding to 14,162 genes in mouse. Here we report two elements from the analyses of |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
these data: alternative promoters and data consistency of DBTSS with the Eukaryote Promoter Databaase |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
(EPD) [3]. We also report the addition of TSS information on zebrafish, malaria, and schyzon. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
2 Methods |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-1 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
The TSS information from DBTSS was used to determine alternative promoters. First, TSSs located inside a |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
RefSeq gene exon, with exception of the first one, were removed in order to avoid artifacts caused by |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
truncated 5’-ends. We then clustered the remaining TSSs, each cluster being separated by at least 500 bases. |XML| xmlLoc_5 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
We finally defined these clusters as alternative promoters. We determined alternative promoters from both |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
human and mouse TSS information. An example for the A kinase anchor protein 1 is shown in Figure 1. A |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
more precise definition of alternative promoters will be reported elsewhere [4]. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
To compare our TSS data with that of the EPD, we mapped the human promoter sequences in EPD 82 to |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
the human genome and determine TSS for EPD data. |XML| xmlLoc_6 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
3 Results and Discussion |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_yes xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_largest-1 xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
It is reported that at least half of the genes have alternative splicing forms [5]; however, the frequency of |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
alternative promoters has not been investigated yet. According to our classification, 6,954 human and 9,886 |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mouse genes have only one promoter while 8,308 human and 4,276 mouse genes turned out to have |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
alternative promoters. Our results suggest that alternative promoters are not so rare in both genomes. |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
To check the quality of our data, we compared them with the EPD data. There are 1,871 human |XML| xmlLoc_7 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
Figure 1: An example of alternative promoters. |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
A kinase anchor protein 1 of both human and |XML| xmlLoc_1 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
mouse are shown. |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
promoters collected from literature in EPD. Among them, we could map 1,767 promoter sequences to the |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
human genome. 1,639 promoters (92.8%) were mapped within 100 bases of the DBTSS TSSs. In fact, EPD |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
contains data based on a full-length cDNA project that uses the same experimental techniques as the cDNA |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
technique used by DBTSS. Therefore, we removed these data, and compared the remaining data with |XML| xmlLoc_2 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
DBTSS alternative promoters. There are 138 alternative promoters in the reduced EPD dataset, 108 (80.6%) |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
corresponding to those of DBTSS. This indicates that the data in DBTSS is consistent with the data obtained |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
from ordinary methods. |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
As shown in Table 1, we have added data from 32,263 zebrafish (Danio rerio), 10,236 malaria |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
(Plasmodium falciparum), and 22,923 schyzon (Cyanidioscyzon merolae) 5’-end clones. These |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
correspond to 3,061 zebrafish, 1,527 malaria and 3,635 schyzon genes on genome sequences, and |XML| xmlLoc_3 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
should be useful for comparative promoter analysis. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_continue bi_xmlPara_continue
We will continue to expand DBTSS by adding other information such as microarray expression |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_smaller xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_new
data. We also plan to report the tissue-specificity of genes using a comparative genomics approach. |XML| xmlLoc_4 xmlBold_no xmlItalic_no xmlFontSize_common xmlPic_no xmlTable_no xmlBullet_no bi_xmlSFBIA_new bi_xmlPara_continue
